The '''J. Willard and Alice Sheets Marriott School of Management''' (MSM) is a [[business school]] located in [[Provo, Utah]] at [[Brigham Young University]] (BYU), a private university in the United States of America owned by [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church). Going by several different names since its inception in 1891, the business school at BYU has been known as the Marriott School of Management since 1988, when [[Marriott International]] founders [[J. Willard Marriott|J. Willard]] and [[Alice Marriott]] made a $15 million donation to the school. The MSM is housed on-campus in the [[N. Eldon Tanner Building]] and offers four undergraduate and seven graduate degrees.

Ethical decision-making is strongly emphasized at the school: undergraduate students are required to complete 14 hours of religion coursework for graduation, all MSM students must take at least one course in management [[ethics]], and both students and faculty must commit to abide by the [[Brigham Young University Honor Code|university's honor code]]. The school also exhibits a unique culture because the majority of its student and faculty bodies are members of the LDS Church.

Many MSM students obtain a level of foreign language proficiency while serving as [[Missionary (LDS Church)|LDS missionaries]]. (Seventy-five percent of the student body is [[Multilingualism|bilingual]], while 30 percent is [[Multilingualism|trilingual]].) Consequently, the Marriott School sponsors high-proficiency business language courses in 11 languages.{{cn|date=August 2012}} The school claims over 44,000 alumni and is accredited by the [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business]].

==History==
In 1891, Brigham Young Academy, the predecessor to BYU, formed the ''Commercial College'', which offered coursework in business education. A decade later (1901), the college began offering its first four-year degree program.<ref name="Lucky7">{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/marriottmag/fall09/features/feature05.cfm |title=Lucky Number Seven |author= |year=2009 |work= |publisher=''Marriott Magazine'' |accessdate=2010-01-12}}</ref> After Brigham Young Academy was separated into [[Brigham Young High School]] and Brigham Young University in 1903,<ref name="byhigh">{{cite web |url=http://www.byhigh.org/History/HistoryDecades/From1903to1920.html |title=Brigham Young High School History |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Brigham Young High School |accessdate=2010-01-12}}</ref> the college was renamed the ''College of Commerce and Business Administration'' as part of the university. The next decade was tough for the college, as "BYU struggled through the [[World War I]], a [[flu epidemic]] [that] closed the school during the fall term of 1918, and school indebtedness that resulted in the 1918 LDS purchase of both BYU's assets and debts."<ref name="Old history">{{cite book |title=International Dictionary of University Histories |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors=Carol J. Summerflied, Mary Elizabeth Devine, Anthony Levi |year=1998 |publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn Publishers |location= |isbn= 978-1-884964-23-7|page= |pages=52<U+2013>55 |url=http://books.google.com/?id=6x3S8eM3spAC&pg=PA54&lpg=PA54&dq=College+of+Commerc-e+and+Business+Administration+BYU+World+War+II&q=College%20of%20Commerce%20and%20Business%20Administration%20BYU%20World%20War%20II |accessdate=2010-01-15 |author1=Summerfield, Carol J}}</ref> Starting in 1921, the college was housed in the [[List of Brigham Young University buildings#Administrative buildings|Maeser Building]], where it would remain for 13 years.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://honors.byu.edu/Main/Information/info_building.aspx | title = Maeser Building History | publisher = [[Brigham Young University]] | accessdate = 2008-05-25 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071218130223/http://honors.byu.edu/Main/Information/info_building.aspx |archivedate = December 18, 2007}}</ref>

The [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]] significantly depleted LDS Church funds, which caused the church to consider closing BYU. However, "the transference of a number of church junior colleges allowed BYU to remain in operation."<ref name="Old history"/> By 1935 the church regained its financial footing and provided more aid to BYU, the school growing slowly over the next ten years. The business college subsequently began offering master's degrees in 1939;<ref name="Lucky7"/> however, the programs were hit hard beginning in 1941 when its enrollment (particularly that of men) dropped due to U.S. involvement in [[World War II]].<ref name="Old history"/> But later that decade, U.S. military veterans returned to school, and in 1945 enrollment doubled. William F. Edwards oversaw the college's growth over the next several years until 1957,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/BYUPhotos&CISOPTR=640&CISOBOX=1&REC=17 |title=William F. Edwards |accessdate=2010-01-16 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]}}</ref> when the school was re-branded as the ''College of Business'' and [[Weldon J. Taylor]] was appointed as its first dean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?id=53 |title=First BYU Business Dean Dies at 92 |accessdate=2008-05-01 |date=2000-08-24 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref><ref name="urlBYU Management Society:">{{cite web |url=https://marriottschool.byu.edu/mgtsoc/members/chapter_webpage.cfm?chapter_id=95 |title=BYU Management Society: |publisher=Marriott School |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref> A year later (1958) the business school held its first management conference, and in 1960 the school was moved to the newly completed [[Jesse Knight Building]].<ref name="Lucky7"/>
[[File:MaeserBuilding.JPG|thumb|right|alt=A granite building with a pillared facade.|The [[Maeser Building]] housed the business school from 1921-60.]]
A [[Master of Business Administration]] (MBA) program was added in 1961, and the school formed its National Advisory Council in 1966. In 1973, the school bestowed its first International Executive of the Year Award to [[AT&T]] President [[Robert D. Lilley]].<ref name="Lucky7"/> Bruce B. Orton served as interim dean of the school for a year until 1975, when [[Merrill J. Bateman]] was recruited from a management position at candy-maker [[Mars, Incorporated|Mars, Inc.]] for the job as dean. That same year, the school was separated into the ''School of Management'' for undergraduate studies and the ''Graduate School of Management'', which grouped together the MBA, [[Master of Public Administration|MPA]], [[M.O.B.|MOB]], and [[MAcc]] programs.<ref name="Lucky7"/> A year later (1976), the business school created a [[BYU School of Accountancy|School of Accountancy]] within its jurisdiction and printed its first issue of ''Exchange'' magazine (now ''Marriott Alumni Magazine''). In 1977, the BYU Management Society was organized.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://marriottschool.byu.edu/mgtsoc/members/chapter_webpage.cfm?chapter_id=39 |title=BYU Management Society |author= |date= |work= |publisher=BYU Management Society |accessdate=2010-01-12}}</ref>

In 1979, [[William G. Dyer]] became dean of the school.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dyerteambuilding.com/about-us.php |title=About Dyer & Associates|author= |date= |work= |publisher=[http://dyerteambuilding.com/index.php Dyer & Associates] |accessdate=2010-01-12}}</ref> Dyer oversaw the construction of the [[N. Eldon Tanner Building]], which was dedicated in 1982. In 1983, an [[Executive MBA]] program was added,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/bschools/01/emba_profiles/byu.htm |title=Executive MBA Profile |author= |year=2001 |work= |publisher=''[[BusinessWeek]]'' |accessdate=2010-01-12}}</ref> and in 1984 [[Paul H. Thompson]] was appointed dean of the school. Two years later (1986), the International Student Sponsor Program was started, which continues to provide financial assistance to married LDS international students to this day. In 1988, the name of the school was changed to ''Marriott'' School of Management in honor of its benefactors<U+2014>[[Marriott International]] founders [[J. Willard Marriott|J. Willard]] and [[Alice Marriott]]<ref name="MarriottFacts">{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/fact/ |title=School Fact Sheet |publisher=Marriott School |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref><U+2014>following their $15 million donation to the school.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE3DC1039F93BA25750C0A96E958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |title= Be It Wharton or Darla Moore, Not for Nothing Is a B-School So Named |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | first = Leslie | last = Wayne | date=1998-03-18 |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref> That same year, the [[U.S. Army|Army]] and [[U.S. Air Force|Air Force]] [[ROTC]] programs became a part of the Marriott School.<ref name="Lucky7"/>

In 1989, [[K. Fred Skousen]] became dean of the school. In that year, the school's endowment exceeded $10 million, and the school was awarded a Center for International Business Education and Research (CIBER) grant by the [[U.S. Department of Education]]. In 1993, the Organizational Leadership and Strategy Department was created, and a year later the school instituted a limited-enrollment policy. Also in 1994, the school began offering a minor in management. By 1998, the school's endowment had reached $40 million and the Institute of Public Management was renamed in honor of [[George W. Romney]], who during his lifetime served as [[Chairman]] of [[American Motors|American Motors Corporation]], [[Governor of Michigan|Governor]] of [[Michigan]], and [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|U.S. Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]]. That same year, [[Ned C. Hill]] was named dean of the Marriott School.<ref name="Lucky7"/>

The school's Center for Economic Self-Reliance (CESR) was formed in 2003,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldextra.com/content/view/72109/ |title=BYU conference centered around movement dedicated to creating jobs, fighting poverty |publisher= ''[[Daily Herald (Utah)|The Daily Herald]]'' | first = Stephen | last = Chapek | date=2003-03-14 |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref> and the Information Systems Department was created in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?id=241 |title=School of Accountancy and Information Systems Separate |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> That same year the CESR also participated in the production of the [[microcredit]] documentary ''Small Fortunes'', which aired nationwide on October 27, 2005, on [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pbs.org/kbyu/smallfortunes/ |title=Small Fortunes |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=[[Public Broadcasting Service]] |work=PBS Feature Programming }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?id=250 |title=Microcredit Documentary to Air Nationwide October 27 on Public Television |date=2005-10-24 |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> In 2006 the school's worldwide initiatives were organized under the Kay and Yvonne Whitmore Global Management Center, named for former [[Kodak]] [[CEO]] [[Kay Whitmore]] and his wife.<ref name="urlGlobal Management">{{cite web |url=http://www.aacsb.edu/publications/enewsline/archive_print/vol5-issue3.pdf |title=BYU Names Global Management Center for former Eastman Kodak Chief Executive |date=2006-02-22 |publisher=[[The Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business]] |work=AACSB eNewsline |accessdate=2008-05-01|format=PDF}}</ref>

In 2006, members of the school's faculty were involved in controversy surrounding the [[Republican Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2008|U.S. Republican Party presidential primaries]]. On October 9, Dean Hill and Associate Dean W. Steve Albrecht sent an e-mail to 50 BYU Management Society members and 100 members of the school's National Advisory Council asking them to support [[Mitt Romney]]'s bid for the U.S. presidency. Hill and Albrecht signed the message with their official BYU titles, sent the e-mail from a BYU e-mail address, and began the message "Dear Marriott School Friend." Both the LDS Church and BYU, as [[tax-exempt]], [[nonprofit organizations]], are [[Campaign finance in the United States#Corporate and union activity|prohibited by federal law]] from endorsing a particular candidate or political party. Albrecht said that he should not have sent it in his capacity as a BYU dean: "It wasn't something BYU did, it wasn't something I probably should have done, and it was bad judgment."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2006/10/19/romney_camp_consulted_with_mormon_leaders/?page=1 |title=Romney camp consulted with Mormon leaders |accessdate=2008-08-06 |last=Helman |first=Scott  |date=2006-10-19  |publisher=''[[Boston Globe]]''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newwest.net/index.php/city/article/political_neutrality_the_lds_romney_connection_it_may_all_be_innocent_but_i/C104/L104/ |title="Political Neutrality" The LDS-Romney Connection: It may all be innocent, but it sure looks bad |accessdate=2008-08-06 |last=Seigal |first=Amy |coauthors= |date=2006-10-25 |work= |publisher=''[http://www.newwest.net/saltlakecity/ New West]''}}</ref>

By 2007, the school's endowment reached $130 million, and in 2008, the Tanner Building Addition was dedicated. For 2011, the endowment reached $137.6 million.<ref name="Endowment">{{cite journal|title=2011 Annual Report|journal=Marriott Alumni Magazine|date=Summer 2012|page=44}}</ref> Also during this year, the Finance Department was formed in an effort to strengthen curriculum and placement;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?article=423 |title=New Finance Department Announced |date=2008-12-15 |accessdate=2010-01-20 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> the Center for Entrepreneurship and Technology was created in honor of former [[Dell]] [[CEO]] [[Kevin Rollins]] and his wife Debra;<ref>{{cite press release | title = New Rollins Center for Entrepreneurship and Technology Created  | publisher = Marriott School of Management  | date = February 25, 2009   | url = http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?article=439 | accessdate = }}</ref> and administrators announced the addition of a Recreation Management and Youth Leadership (RMYL) Department to the school. The latter department was formerly under BYU's College of Health and Human Performance and comrpises the academic disciplines of leisure services management, therapeutic recreation, [[Scouting]] administration, [[Non-profit organization|non-profit]] management, and youth leadership.<ref>{{cite web | title = Scouting for a Bachelor's Degree  | publisher = ''American Scouting Digest''  | year = 2003 | url = http://www.scoutingdigest.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=453&Itemid=79| accessdate =2010-01-20 }} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

==Campus==
{{See also|Brigham Young University campus|List of Brigham Young University buildings}}
[[File:TNRB Tanner Building.jpg|thumb|right|250px|alt=Large, gray, rectangular building with rows of windows lining every other floor|The [[N. Eldon Tanner Building]] was expanded 53 percent in 2008 to accommodate the Marriott School's growth.]]
The Marriott School is located on the campus of [[Brigham Young University]], which is situated in the urban, [[Wasatch Front]] area of [[Provo, Utah]]. The school is principally housed inside the [[N. Eldon Tanner Building]] (TNRB). At the building's construction announcement in 1980, university President [[Dallin H. Oaks]] said that the Board of Trustees named it in honor of [[N. Eldon Tanner]] (a Canadian politician and counselor to four [[President of the Church|presidents]] of the LDS Church) because he was known in Canada as "Mr. Integrity"<U+2014>a title wished upon every Marriott School graduate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://speeches.byu.edu/reader/reader.php?id=6156 |title=N. Eldon Tanner: An Example to Follow |accessdate=2008-05-07 |last=Romney |first=Marion G. |date=1977-12-04 |work=Speeches |publisher=[[Intellectual Reserve|Intellectual Reserve, Inc.]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/marriottmag/fall07/deans_message.cfm |title=Mr. Integrity |accessdate=2008-05-07 |last=Ogden |first=Joseph |date=2007-09-01 |publisher= Marriott School |work=Marriott Magazine}}</ref> At the [[groundbreaking]] for the building on November 8, 1980, "explosives that were used to remove the soil showered unsuspecting spectators with dust and pebbles."<ref name="Lucky7"/> The Tanner Building was completed in late 1982 and dedicated on April 5, 1983, by [[Gordon B. Hinckley]].<ref name="tanner_building">{{cite web |url=http://www.lds.org/ldsfoundation/accelwork/humanintereststory/0,7989,599-1-3-2536,00.html  |title=Ground Broken for N. Eldon Tanner Building Addition at BYU |date=2007-06-12 |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher=[[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] |work=LDS Philanthropies |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071204191116/http://www.lds.org/ldsfoundation/accelwork/humanintereststory/0,7989,599-1-3-2536,00.html |archivedate = 2007-12-04}}</ref> Today, the seven-story, {{convert|120000|sqft|m2}} granite building houses Marriott School classrooms as well as professor and administration offices. A {{convert|76000|sqft|m2}} addition, costing $43 million and funded by donations, was dedicated on October 24, 2008 by alumnus [[Thomas S. Monson]].<ref>{{cite journal| last =Crane  | first = Sarah E.  | title = A Bigger, Better Business Building  | journal = BYU Magazine  | page = 10  | publisher = [[Brigham Young University]] | location = [[Provo, Utah]]  | date = Winter 2009  | url =    }}</ref> The addition increased the building's capacity by 53 percent and provides 10 tiered classrooms, one network teaching room, one large assembly room, and 39 study rooms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ldschurchnews.com/articles/55644/Tanner-addition-dedicated-at-BYU.html |title=Tanner Addition Dedicated at BYU |accessdate=2010-01-19 |last=Taylor |first=Scott |date=2008-10-31 |publisher= ''[[Deseret News]]''}}</ref>

The Tanner Building is located directly west of central campus. To its immediate north is the [[Gordon B. Hinckley Alumni and Visitors Center]] and on-campus housing Helaman Halls. Its western and southern sides are covered by athletic facilities. Close by is also the newly renovated [[Jesse Knight Building]] (JKB), where some business school classes are held. Additionally, a parking garage is located adjacent to the Tanner Building.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsnet.byu.edu/story.cfm/64066 |title=Tanner Building Gets Expanded |last=Russell |first=Casey |date=2007-04-13 |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher = ''[[The Daily Universe]]'' }}</ref>

==Academics==
===Organization and research===
