As part of the larger institution of BYU, the Marriott School is ultimately administered by [[List of presidents of Brigham Young University|BYU's President]] and Board of Trustees. Under them, the school is directly managed by a Dean (currently [[Gary C. Cornia]]), who is advised by two associate deans and the school's National Advisory Council.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/emp/dept.cfm |title=Marriott School Faculty and Staff Departmental Directory |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080417064611/http://marriottschool.byu.edu/emp/dept.cfm <!--Added by H3llBot--> |archivedate=2008-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?id=385 |title=Gary Cornia Named Dean of BYU<U+2019>s Marriott School of Management |date=2008-05-28 |accessdate=2008-05-29 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> The school has nine academic departments,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://saas.byu.edu/catalog/2009-2010ucat/colleges/MSM.php |title=MSM Departments |accessdate=2010-01-21 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]}}</ref> each overseen by a [[Chair (academic)|department chair]]. The MSM student body has its own [[student council]], which serves an umbrella organization for MSM clubs. The school houses student chapters for national associations including the [[Society for Human Resource Management]], the [[Collegiate Entrepreneurs' Organization]], [[Rotaract]], and [[Net Impact]]. There is also a chapter of the honorary association [[Beta Alpha Psi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/clubs/ |title=MSM Club List |accessdate=2010-01-20 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref>

Faculty are grouped in one or more of seven "academic areas": accounting, business management (including business law, management communication, managerial economics, marketing, and supply-chain management), finance, information systems, organizational leadership and strategy, public management, and recreation management and youth leadership. The school is also home to four research centers that organize research in different fields of business administration and establish liaisons between the Marriott School and the corporate world. Both undergraduate and graduate students may be invited to work as [[teaching assistant|teaching]] and [[research assistant]]s, and some MAcc students teach accounting classes during the spring or summer terms, as well as at the [[Brigham_Young_University_campus#BYU_Salt_Lake_Center|BYU's Salt Lake Center]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ce.byu.edu/sl/ |title=BYU Salt Lake Center |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]}}</ref> However, research productivity is hampered by the fact that the MSM has no doctoral programs, and therefore, no doctoral students focused on research.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/bschools/98/next25/comments14.htm |title=MSM Profile |accessdate=2010-01-20 |year=1998 |publisher=''[[BusinessWeek]]''}}</ref> The MSM faculty was ranked #64 nationally and #71 globally in 2008 for its research productivity in the ''[[University of Texas at Dallas|UTD]] Top 100 Business School Research Ranking''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://som.utdallas.edu/top100Ranking/ |title=UTD Top 100 Business School Research Ranking |accessdate=2010-01-20 |year=2008 |publisher=[[University of Texas at Dallas]]}}</ref>

The Marriott School oversees two perennial publications: ''Economic Self-Reliance'' (a semi-annual, practitioner-focused publication that highlights research and best practices) and ''Marriott Alumni Magazine'' (a tri-annual publication that showcases innovative business research and ideas as well as news from the school and alumni).<ref name="MarriottFacts"/> Marriott School students and faculty are serviced by the Business and Economics Library within the [[Harold B. Lee Library]], which houses an accounting lab and several [[Bloomberg Terminal]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lib.byu.edu/sites/business/ |title=Business and Economics Library |accessdate=2010-01-20 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]}}</ref> The MSM is accredited by the [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business]].<ref name="urlAACSB International">{{cite web |url=https://datadirect.aacsb.edu/public/profiles/profile.cfm?runReport=1&unitid=54419&userType=All |title=Brigham Young University|publisher=[[The Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business]]  |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref><ref name="urlBYU:UndergradProfile<U+2013>BusinessWeek">{{cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/bschools/rankings/undergraduate_mba_profiles/byu.html |title=Brigham Young University: Undergraduate Profile&ndash;BusinessWeek |publisher=''[[BusinessWeek]]'' |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref>

===Curriculum and degrees offered===
[[File:Tanner building interior.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Large open building with granite steps running up the left side of the multi-storey building and modern fountains centered on each floor|The [[Atrium (architecture)|atrium]] of the [[N. Eldon Tanner Building|Tanner Building's]] east wing]]
The MSM offers four [[Bachelor of Science]] degree programs: [[Accounting]], [[Information Systems]], [[Management]], and Recreation Management and Young Leadership. Three minors are also offered to all students of BYU: Management, Non-profit Management, and Strategy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/ |title=Marriott School Programs |publisher=Marriott School |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref> Management majors must further choose one of the following areas of emphasis: Entrepreneurship, Finance, General Business, Global Supply Chain Management, Marketing, Organizational Behavior and Human Resources, or Strategy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/mba/ |title=MSM MBA |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref>

The school offers seven graduate degrees: the [[MAcc]], [[MBA]], [[Executive MBA|EMBA]], [[Master of Public Administration|EMPA]], [[MISM]], [[Master of Public Administration|MPA]], and Master of Youth and Family Recreation. MBA students choose a major (Finance, Marketing, Supply Chain Management, [[List of graduate degree programs in human resources management|OBHR]], or Product Development) and a minor (Entrepreneurship, International Business, Strategy) if desired.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/mba/curriculum/minors.cfm |title=MBA Minors |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref><ref name="urlMajors">{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/mba/curriculum/majors.cfm?sitePageId=1157 |title=MBA Majors |publisher=Marriott School |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref> MAcc students choose either audit, tax, or Ph.D. Prep.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/soa/curriculum/ |title=MAcc Curriculum |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080511221230/http://marriottschool.byu.edu/soa/curriculum/ <!--Added by H3llBot--> |archivedate=2008-05-11}}</ref>

Matriculation into the Marriott School as an undergraduate requires an application independent from normal acceptance to BYU. Once in the program, students go through a one-semester "core" where students in the block are in the same classes together as teams.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/management/core.cfm |title=Management Integrated Core Program |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> All undergraduates must also complete a one-semester mentoring program where each student selects a Marriott School alumnus to converse with over the course of the semester.<ref name="MarriottFacts"/> The MSM's class schedules mirror those of the university: two 16-week semesters (fall and winter) and two terms over the summer break (spring and summer). Students must carry 12 credit hours in order to be considered a full-time student, and 18 credit hours is the maximum unless permission is granted to take more.

About 70% of student [[tuition]] is funded by LDS Church [[tithe|tithing]] funds, making tuition less expensive for church members than at similar private universities. Students not members of the church pay double the LDS tuition rate.<ref>{{cite web| last =Madsen| first =Grant| title =BYU number two value after BYU-Hawaii, says "Consumers Digest"| publisher =[[Brigham Young University]] | date= 2004-05-04| url =http://byunews.byu.edu/release.aspx?story=archive04/may/cdigest | accessdate = 2007-08-19  |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071118203138/http://byunews.byu.edu/release.aspx?story=archive04/may/cdigest |archivedate = 2007-11-18}}</ref> For the 2010-2011 school year, MSM tuition for full-time LDS undergraduates was $2,210 per semester; for MSM graduate students, it was $5,140 per semester.<ref>{{cite web| title =BYU Tuition | publisher =[[Brigham Young University]] | year= 2010 | url =http://home.byu.edu/webapp/finserve/content/page/Tuition.html#t1 | accessdate = 2010-01-21 }}</ref> All MSM students may apply for several school-specific and university-wide financial aid opportunities. Some are program-specific, others are need-based. The ''Hawes Scholars'' program is the highest scholarship distinction given to MBA students at the school. The program awards $10,000 to second-year students who are nominated by students or faculty, and who are then selected based on academic performance, leadership maturity, and a commitment to high ethical standards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?article=442 |title=Marriott School Announces 2009 Hawes Scholars |date=2009-03-04 |accessdate=2010-01-21 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref>

All Marriott School students may also earn the ''Global Management Certificate''. To earn the certificate, students are required to take a business language course, pertinent international business classes, and participate in an international field study or study abroad program.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/gmc/programs/certificate.cfm |title=Global Management Certificate |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> Undergraduate students may also qualify for graduation honors. ''[[Brigham Young University Honors Program|University Honors]]'' is the highest distinction BYU awards its graduates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ccc.byu.edu/honors |title=Honors |accessdate=2010-01-21 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Overseen by [[Brigham Young University Honors Program|Honors Program]], the distinction requires students to complete an honors curriculum requirement, a Great Works requirement, an Advanced Languages requirement, a service requirement, an honors thesis requirement, a graduation portfolio that summarizes the student's honors experiences<U+2014>all while maintaining at least a 3.5 GPA.<ref name="honors"/> The Marriott School designates a faculty member as its Honors Coordinator, who aids students in finding faculty with whom to begin honors thesis research.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://honors.byu.edu/Main/files/Honors%20Thesis%20Guidelines%20for%20the%20Marriott%20School.pdf |title=Completing an Honors Thesis in the Marriott School |accessdate=2010-01-21 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]}}</ref> The university also awards [[Latin honors|Latin scholastic distinctions]]: ''summa cum laude'' top 1 percent, ''magna cum laude'' top 5 percent, and ''cum laude'' top 10 percent.<ref name="honors">{{cite web |url=http://saas.byu.edu/catalog/2009-2010ucat/GeneralInfo/Graduation.php#LatinScholDistinctions |title=BYU Graduation Honors |accessdate=2010-01-21 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]}}</ref>

===Rankings, awards, and admissions===
Many of the Marriott School's degree programs have received high rankings from independent sources. In 2009, the Marriott School's undergraduate programs were ranked #5 by ''[[BusinessWeek]]''.<ref name="USUnivRankings_BW">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/bschools/rankings/ |title=Business School Rankings and Profiles |year=2010 |author=|publisher= ''[[BusinessWeek]]'' |accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref> The MSM's MBA program received rankings from several sources for 2009: #22 ranking by ''BusinessWeek'',<ref name="USUnivRankings_BW"/> #16 by ''[[Forbes]]'',<ref name="USUnivRankings_Forbes">{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/lists/2011/95/best-business-schools-11_land.html |title=Best Business Schools |year=2011|author= |publisher= ''[[Forbes]]'' |accessdate=2011-10-16}}</ref> and #29 by ''U.S. News & World Report''.<ref name="USUnivRankings_USNWRg">{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-business-schools/mba-rankings |title=Best Business Schools |year=2011 |author= |publisher= ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' |accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref> Among regional schools the program was ranked #1 by ''[[The Wall Street Journal|The Wall Street Journal's]]'' most recent ranking (2007);<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.harrisinteractive.com/services/bschools.asp |title=Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive Business School Survey |accessdate=2008-05-30 |publisher=[[Harris Interactive]]}}</ref> and among business schools worldwide the MBA program was ranked #92 for 2009 by ''[[Financial Times]]''.<ref name="USUnivRankings_FT">{{cite web|url=http://rankings.ft.com/businessschoolrankings/global-mba-rankings-2011 |title=Global MBA Rankings |year=2011 |author= |publisher= ''[[Financial Times]]'' |accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref> The program was also ranked #1 for the amount of time to payback (''BusinessWeek'', 2006)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bwnt.businessweek.com/bschools/06/mba_payback.asp |title=The High Price of Admission |accessdate=2008-05-30 |publisher=''[[BusinessWeek]]''}}</ref> and #2 for its emphasis on ethics (''The Wall Street Journal'', 2007).<ref name="urlDeseretNewsYgets2">{{cite web |url=http://deseretnews.com/dn/view/0,1249,510055046,00.html |last=Walch |first=Tad |title=Y gets #2 ethics ranking |publisher=''[[Deseret News]]'' |date=2003-09-18 |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref>
{{Infobox business school rankings
