The Marriott School's [[BYU School of Accountancy|accounting program]] is the only program in the country to receive the [[American Accounting Association|American Accounting Association's]] ''Innovation in Accounting Education Award'' twice. The first award, received in 1993, was for the development of an integrated approach to teaching accounting. The second award, received in 2007, was for the development of a [[BYU School of Accountancy#Ph.D. Prep Track|Ph.D. Prep Track]] to prepare MAcc students to enroll in a Ph.D. program after graduation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://phdprep.byu.edu/ |title=PhD Prep |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]}}</ref> For 2009, the bachelor's degree in the SOA received two #3 rankings, one by ''[[Public Accounting Report]]'' and the other by ''U.S. News & World Report''.<ref name="PAR">{{cite web | url = http://gmatclub.com/forum/public-accounting-report-2009-ranking-undergrad-ms-phd-88331.html | title = 2009 Accounting Program Rankings | publisher = ''[[Public Accounting Report]]'' |year=2009 | accessdate = 2010-01-19 }}</ref><ref name="USNWR_BSAcc">{{cite web | url = http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/spec-accounting | title = Ranking of undergraduate accounting programs | publisher = ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' |year=2009 | accessdate = 2010-01-19 }}</ref> The same two reporting agencies also ranked the school's MAcc program #3 and #8 in the nation, respectively.<ref name="PAR"/><ref name="USNWR_MAcc">{{cite web | url = http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-business-schools/accounting | title = Ranking of graduate accounting programs | publisher = ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' |year=2009 | accessdate = 2010-01-19 }}</ref>

The Information Systems department was ranked #26 in the nation in 2003 for research,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://isys.byu.edu/Menus/Bachelors/Overview.cfm  |title=Bachelors of Information Systems |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]] |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071114081440/http://isys.byu.edu/Menus/Bachelors/Overview.cfm |archivedate = 2007-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?id=159 |title=BYU Information Systems Research Ranked in Top Thirty |date=2003-10-08 |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> and its MISM program was ranked "among the top ten" by ''[[TechRepublic]]'' in 2008.<ref>TechRepublic does not rank by number; it only establishes the top 10. {{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?ID=419 |date=2008-11-18 |title=BYU Information Systems Program Among Top Ten |accessdate=2010-01-08 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref>

The Marriott School is one of the few colleges at BYU that requires application from undergraduate students post-matriculation to the university itself. In addition to essays and pre-baccalaureate academics, students are evaluated on performance in 13 credit hours of "pre-management" coursework at BYU.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/undergrad/PreManagementGuidebook.pdf |title=Pre-Management |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> For 2008, the MSM admitted 69 percent of undergraduate applicants, comprising a class of 1,783 students.<ref name="BW_Under"/>

Applicants to the MBA program are evaluated based on commitment to the mission of BYU and the LDS Church, undergraduate academic performance, [[Graduate Management Admission Test]] (GMAT) standardized test scores, essays, work experience, recommendations, written applications, and interviews, if applicable. For 2009, the MBA program admitted 51 percent of applicants or 478 students. The class averaged 672 on the GMAT, 3.54 GPA, and 45 months of work experience post-baccalaureate.<ref name="BW_MBA"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/career/recruiters/classProfile.cfm |title=MBA Class Profile |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref>

==Programs and Institutes==
=== Melvin J. Ballard Center for Economic Self-Reliance ===
The Melvin J. Ballard Center for Economic Self-Reliance is an organization that focuses on social innovation and working with students in both the Marriott School and other parts of BYU to help them develop methods to solve societal problems.<ref>[http://marriottschool.byu.edu/selfreliance/about/whoweare Ballard Center mission description page]</ref>  It is currently headed by Todd Manwaring, with [[W. Gibb Dyer]], the [[O. Leslie Stone]] Professor of Entrepreneurship as the Academic Director.

The Center was organized in 2003 and named for Ballard in 2010.<ref>[http://news.byu.edu/archive10-apr-ballard.aspx BYU Press Release on naming of the Ballard Center]</ref>

==People==
===Students ===
The Marriott School student body comprises approximately 1,900 undergraduate and 1,100 graduate students. Nearly 75 percent of the students are [[bilingual]] and about 30 percent speak a third language, most having lived abroad while serving a [[Mission (LDS Church)|mission]] for the LDS Church.<ref name="MarriottFacts"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?id=266 |title=Global Management Center Named for Former Kodak CEO |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> Approximately 16 percent of students are international students, 66 percent are married, and [[White people|whites]] ([[Hispanic|non-Hispanic]]) comprise 91 percent of the student body as of 2009.<ref name="BW_MBA">{{cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/bschools/rankings/full_time_mba_profiles/byu.html |title=Brigham Young University |accessdate=2010-01-15 |publisher=''[[BusinessWeek]]'' |year=2009}}</ref> Eighty-seven percent of domestic students hail from the West.<ref name="BW_MBA"/> The mean and median ages of undergraduate students is 23, 21 percent of whom are female.<ref name="BW_Under"/> Female MBA students only account for 13 percent of the graduating class.<ref name="BW_MBA"/>

The Marriott School embodies a distinct [[Brigham_Young_University#LDS_atmosphere|culture]] due to its affiliation with the LDS Church. "Membership in The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints is not required for admittance into the [school], but an understanding of and a commitment to support the Church's mission is necessary."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/mba/admissions/admission_criteria.cfm |title=MBA Admission Criteria |accessdate=2010-01-21 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> All students must adhere to the university's [[Brigham Young University Honor Code|honor code]], which prescribes standards of [[Chastity|morality]], [[Dress code|dress and grooming]], academic honesty, and [[Teetotalism|drug and alcohol non-consumption]]. Undergraduate students must also take 14 credit hours of religion courses in order to fulfill the university's religious education requirement for graduation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://religion.byu.edu/rel_req.php |title=BYU Religion Requirement |author= |date= |work= |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]] |accessdate=2010-01-15}}</ref>
[[File:Stephen Covey 2010.jpg|thumb|upright|right|alt=Older, bald man in a sharp suit speaking to an unseen audience|Author and professional speaker [[Stephen Covey|Stephen R. Covey]], former Marriott School professor]]

Students find diversion in clubs sponsored by the MSM and in university-wide [[intramural sports]]. One of the newest and exciting is the [http://www.businessphd.byu.edu Marriott School of Management Pre-doctoral Student Organization]. Students also compete in academic competitions at various campuses and venues. A BYU student team placed #1 at the [[University of Arizona|University of Arizona's]] annual ethics competition (''Duel in the Desert'') in 2006 and 2007,<ref name="url5th Annual Duel in the Desert">{{cite web |date=2007-02-12 |url=http://www.takechargeamerica.org/about-us/press-room/Pages/5th-annual-duel-in-the-desert-pr.aspx  |title=5th Annual Duel in the Desert |publisher=Take Charge America, Inc. |accessdate=2008-05-01 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080521093857/http://www.takechargeamerica.org/about-us/press-room/Pages/5th-annual-duel-in-the-desert-pr.aspx |archivedate = 2008-05-21}}</ref> and a team of undergraduate accounting students placed #1 in the 2007 [[Deloitte]] Tax Case Competition<U+2014>marking BYU<U+2019>s seventh consecutive first- or second-place finish in this division.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deloitte.com/ |title=Sixth Annual Deloitte Tax Case Study Competition Spotlights Future Tax Professionals |date=2008-02-18 |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=[[Deloitte]]}}</ref>  The BYU chapter of the Collegiate Entrepreneurs Organization also received three first-place national chapter awards at the organization<U+2019>s national conference in Chicago, including "Best in Teaching Entrepreneurship" and "Best Chapter Marketing."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ceo.byu.edu/chicago-trip.html |title=CEO Chicago Trip |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]] |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080407012103/http://ceo.byu.edu/chicago-trip.html <!--Added by H3llBot--> |archivedate=2008-04-07}}</ref> Additionally, a BYU student team was #3 at the 2007 International Venture Capital Investment Competition finals, finishing behind [[MIT]] and the [[University of Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vcic.unc.edu/nationalFinals2007.html |title=VCIC International Finals |publisher=[[University of North Carolina]] |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref>

===Faculty===
{{See also|List of Brigham Young University faculty}}
The Marriott School has 130 full-time faculty with more than 90 percent holding [[Ph.D.]]s.<ref name="MarriottFacts" /> Faculty have included former [[Academy of Management]] president David Whetten,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/emp/employee.cfm?emp=daw4  |title=Faculty Profile: D.A. Whetten |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080304150558/http://marriottschool.byu.edu/emp/employee.cfm?emp=daw4 |archivedate = 2008-03-04}}</ref> [[WordPerfect Corporation|WordPerfect]] co-founder [[Alan Ashton (executive)|Alan Ashton]], [[FranklinCovey]] co-founder [[Stephen Covey]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Entrepreneurship Founders: Stephen Covey |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/advisoryboard/detail.cfm?mem=1173&group=3 |date= |work= |publisher=Marriott School, BYU |accessdate=9 September 2009}}</ref> and Steve Albrecht, former President of the [[Association of Certified Fraud Examiners]] and of the [[American Accounting Association]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/emp/employee.cfm?emp=wsa  |title=Faculty Profile: W.S. Albrecht |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080126045102/http://marriottschool.byu.edu/emp/employee.cfm?emp=wsa |archivedate = 2008-01-26}}</ref>

Several Marriott School faculty have been awarded for their efforts in teaching and research, as well as in the community. Kevin Stocks was awarded the 2007 ''Joseph A. Silvoso Faculty Award of Merit'' by the Federation of Schools of Accountancy for displaying excellence in accounting education,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefsa.org/aprs/silvoso_award.htm |title=Awards |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=The Federation of Schools of Accountancy}}</ref> and Warner Woodworth received the 2007 ''Faculty Pioneer Award in External Impact'' from The Aspen Institute's Center for Business Education in recognition for the integration of social issues in research and teaching.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aspencbe.org/awards/pioneers/winners8.html |title=2007 Faculty Pioneers
| publisher = The Aspen Institute |accessdate=2008-05-01 |work= }}</ref> [[Gary C. Cornia|Gary Cornia]] also received the 2006 ''Stephen D. Gold Award'' from the Association for Public Policy Analysis and Management,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.appam.org/awards/gold.asp |title=APPAM Awards
| publisher = Association for Public Policy Analysis and Management |accessdate=2008-05-01 |format= |work= }}</ref> while Chyleen Arbon was appointed to the Utah Advisory Committee to the [[U.S. Commission on Civil Rights]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/emp/employee.cfm?emp=caa44  |title=Faculty Profile: C.A. Arbon |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080126111025/http://marriottschool.byu.edu/emp/employee.cfm?emp=caa44 |archivedate = 2008-01-26}}</ref>
[[File:Thomas S Monson.jpg|right|thumb|alt=Close-up of older, wrinkled man in conservative suit smiling|[[Thomas S. Monson]] '74, [[President of the Church|President]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]]]

===Alumni===
[[File:KRollins.jpg|thumb|upright|left|alt=Middle-aged man with flowing hair standing in a suit, apparently addressing an audience|[[Kevin Rollins]] '84, former [[CEO]] of [[Dell]]]]
{{See also|List of Brigham Young University alumni}}
Numbering nearly 44,000,<ref name="MarriottFacts"/> graduates from the Marriott School have been deemed "first among recruiters" by ''[[BusinessWeek]]'' in 2008.<ref name="urlNewsReleaseBW_BYU7">{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/news/release.cfm?id=367 |title=BusinessWeek Ranks BYU Undergrad Business #7 |date=2008-02-29 |publisher=Marriott School |accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref> Top recruiters include [[Ernst & Young]], [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]], [[Deloitte & Touche]], [[KPMG]], [[Hewlett-Packard|HP]], [[Intel]], [[Cisco]], and [[Goldman Sachs]].<ref name="urlBYU:UndergradProfile<U+2013>BusinessWeek"/><ref name="BW_MBA"/> For 2009, MBA graduates averaged $87,769 in post-graduation salary, MPA graduates $48,294, MAcc graduates $51,900, MISM graduates $58,785, and management undergraduates $48,995.<ref name="BW_Under">{{cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/bschools/rankings/undergraduate_mba_profiles/byu.html |title=Brigham Young University |accessdate=2010-01-15 |publisher=''[[BusinessWeek]]'' |year=2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/career/recruiters/salaryBonusData.cfm |title=MSM Salary Data |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref>

There is also a strong contingency of Marriott School alumni who pursue a career in [[academia]], with BYU being ranked #8 nationally for the number of students who go on to earn [[Ph.D.|Ph.Ds]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.byu.edu/homepage/mentored.pdf  |title=BYU Undergraduate Research & Mentoring |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]|format=PDF |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080626225747/http://news.byu.edu/homepage/mentored.pdf |archivedate = 2008-06-26}}</ref> This is due in part to the MAcc [[BYU School of Accountancy#Ph.D. Prep Track|Ph.D. Prep Track]] and the [[BYU Honors Program]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://honors.byu.edu/ |title=History of the Honors Program |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]}}</ref>

Alumni of the Marriott School of Management who are prominent in business include [[Citigroup]] [[CFO]] [[Gary Crittenden]] 1976,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citigroup.com/citigroup/press/2007/070225a.htm |title=Citi Names Gary Crittenden as Chief Financial Officer |date=2009-03-20 |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher=[[Citigroup]] |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080503232450/http://www.citigroup.com/citigroup/press/2007/070225a.htm <!--Added by H3llBot--> |archivedate=2008-05-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/marriottmag/fall07/alumni/spotlights.cfm |title=Alumnus Named Citigroup CFO, Marriott School Honored Alumni |year=2007 |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher=[http://marriottschool.byu.edu/marriottmag/fall03/index.cfm Marriott Magazine]}}</ref> former [[Dell]] [[CEO]] [[Kevin Rollins]] 1984,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=266021&symbol=DELL.O |title=Kevin Rollins: Executive Profile |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher=''[[BusinessWeek]]''}}</ref> former [[Intermountain Health Care]] [[CEO]] [[William H. Nelson|Bill Nelson]] '67,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3257/is_12_59/ai_n15980873/?tag=content-inner;col1 | title = Former HFMA chairman receives national award |date=2005-12-01 | publisher = Healthcare Financial Management | accessdate = 2008-06-13 }}</ref> and [[Krispy Kreme|Krispy Kreme International President]] [[Jeffrey B. Welch]] 1984.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.forbes.com/profile/jeffrey-b-welch/47899 |title=Welch Profile |accessdate=2009-10-09 |publisher=''[[Forbes]]''}}</ref><ref name="Fall09">{{cite web |url=http://marriottschool.byu.edu/marriottmag/pdf/2009_Fall.pdf |title=Fall 2009 ''Marriott Magazine'' |accessdate=2009-10-09 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref> In education, [[Alison Davis-Blake]] 1982 is [[Dean (education)|Dean]] of the [[Carlson School of Management]] at the [[University of Minnesota]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carlsonschool.umn.edu/Page2075.aspx?type=faculty&eid=147632404 |title=Dean Davis-Blake's Profile |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher=[[University of Minnesota]]}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> [[John Grout]] 1984 is Dean of the [[Berry College#Campbell School of Business|Campbell School of Business]] at [[Berry College]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.berry.edu/pr/news/pressdetail-pf.asp?ID=451 |last=Woodall |first=Rick |title=Dean Grout's Profile |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher=[[Berry College]]}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and [[David A. Bednar]] 1976 served as president of [[BYU-Idaho]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.byui.edu/president/presbio.html |title=Pres. Bednar Profile |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher=[[Brigham Young University<U+2013>Idaho]]}}</ref> Alumni in other fields include three-time [[NFL]] [[Super Bowl]] champion [[Bart Oates]] 1982 as well as [[Thomas S. Monson]] 1974, [[President of the Church|President]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] and Chairman of the Board of Trustees of BYU.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/O/OateBa00.htm |title=Bart Oates Statistics |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher=''Pro Football Reference'' }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsroom.lds.org/ldsnewsroom/eng/news-releases-stories/biography-of-president-thomas-s-monson |title=Thomas S. Monson's bio |accessdate=2008-05-07 |publisher=[[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080422204903/http://newsroom.lds.org/ldsnewsroom/eng/news-releases-stories/biography-of-president-thomas-s-monson <!--Added by H3llBot--> |archivedate=2008-04-22}}</ref>

Many alumni also choose to participate in the [[BYU Management Society]], which was founded in 1977 by Dean [[Merrill J. Bateman]]. The organization is an alumni association "with inclusivity", inviting non-alumni to join as well. The fourfold mission of the society is networking, career development, supporting BYU and the Marriott School, and community service. The Society membership is now at 6,000 members in 40 U.S. cities and 10 countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://marriottschool.byu.edu/mgtsoc/index.cfm |title=About the Management Society |accessdate=2008-05-01 |publisher=Marriott School}}</ref>

